42勘 1:1 Since many have undertaken to set down an orderly account of the events that have been fulfilled among us,
42勘 1:2 just as they were handed on to us by those who from the beginning were eyewitnesses and servants of the word,
42勘 1:3 I too decided, after investigating everything carefully from the very first, to write an orderly account for you, most excellent Theophilus,
42勘 1:4 so that you may know the truth concerning the things about which you have been instructed.
42勘 1:5 In the days of King Herod of Judea, there was a priest named Zechariah, who belonged to the priestly order of Abijah. His wife was a descendant of Aaron, and her name was Elizabeth.
42勘 1:6 Both of them were righteous before God, living blamelessly according to all the commandments and regulations of the Lord.
42勘 1:7 But they had no children, because Elizabeth was barren, and both were getting on in years.
42勘 1:8 Once when he was serving as priest before God and his section was on duty,
42勘 1:9 he was chosen by lot, according to the custom of the priesthood, to enter the sanctuary of the Lord and offer incense.
42勘 1:10 Now at the time of the incense offering, the whole assembly of the people was praying outside.
42勘 1:11 Then there appeared to him an angel of the Lord, standing at the right side of the altar of incense.
42勘 1:12 When Zechariah saw him, he was terrified; and fear overwhelmed him.
42勘 1:13 But the angel said to him, "Do not be afraid, Zechariah, for your prayer has been heard. Your wife Elizabeth will bear you a son, and you will name him John.
42勘 1:14 You will have joy and gladness, and many will rejoice at his birth,
42勘 1:15 for he will be great in the sight of the Lord. He must never drink wine or strong drink; even before his birth he will be filled with the Holy Spirit.
42勘 1:16 He will turn many of the people of Israel to the Lord their God.
42勘 1:17 With the spirit and power of Elijah he will go before him, to turn the hearts of parents to their children, and the disobedient to the wisdom of the righteous, to make ready a people prepared for the Lord."
42勘 1:18 Zechariah said to the angel, "How will I know that this is so? For I am an old man, and my wife is getting on in years."
42勘 1:19 The angel replied, "I am Gabriel. I stand in the presence of God, and I have been sent to speak to you and to bring you this good news.
42勘 1:20 But now, because you did not believe my words, which will be fulfilled in their time, you will become mute, unable to speak, until the day these things occur."
42勘 1:21 Meanwhile the people were waiting for Zechariah, and wondered at his delay in the sanctuary.
42勘 1:22 When he did come out, he could not speak to them, and they realized that he had seen a vision in the sanctuary. He kept motioning to them and remained unable to speak.
42勘 1:23 When his time of service was ended, he went to his home.
42勘 1:24 After those days his wife Elizabeth conceived, and for five months she remained in seclusion. She said,
42勘 1:25 "This is what the Lord has done for me when he looked favorably on me and took away the disgrace I have endured among my people."
42勘 1:26 In the sixth month the angel Gabriel was sent by God to a town in Galilee called Nazareth,
42勘 1:27 to a virgin engaged to a man whose name was Joseph, of the house of David. The virgin's name was Mary.
42勘 1:28 And he came to her and said, "Greetings, favored one! The Lord is with you."
42勘 1:29 But she was much perplexed by his words and pondered what sort of greeting this might be.
42勘 1:30 The angel said to her, "Do not be afraid, Mary, for you have found favor with God.
42勘 1:31 And now, you will conceive in your womb and bear a son, and you will name him Jesus.
42勘 1:32 He will be great, and will be called the Son of the Most High, and the Lord God will give to him the throne of his ancestor David.
42勘 1:33 He will reign over the house of Jacob forever, and of his kingdom there will be no end."
42勘 1:34 Mary said to the angel, "How can this be, since I am a virgin?"
42勘 1:35 The angel said to her, "The Holy Spirit will come upon you, and the power of the Most High will overshadow you; therefore the child to be born will be holy; he will be called Son of God.
42勘 1:36 And now, your relative Elizabeth in her old age has also conceived a son; and this is the sixth month for her who was said to be barren.
42勘 1:37 For nothing will be impossible with God."
42勘 1:38 Then Mary said, "Here am I, the servant of the Lord; let it be with me according to your word." Then the angel departed from her.
42勘 1:39 In those days Mary set out and went with haste to a Judean town in the hill country,
42勘 1:40 where she entered the house of Zechariah and greeted Elizabeth.
42勘 1:41 When Elizabeth heard Mary's greeting, the child leaped in her womb. And Elizabeth was filled with the Holy Spirit
42勘 1:42 and exclaimed with a loud cry, "Blessed are you among women, and blessed is the fruit of your womb.
42勘 1:43 And why has this happened to me, that the mother of my Lord comes to me?
42勘 1:44 For as soon as I heard the sound of your greeting, the child in my womb leaped for joy.
42勘 1:45 And blessed is she who believed that there would be a fulfillment of what was spoken to her by the Lord."
42勘 1:46 And Mary said, "My soul magnifies the Lord,
42勘 1:47 and my spirit rejoices in God my Savior,
42勘 1:48 for he has looked with favor on the lowliness of his servant. Surely, from now on all generations will call me blessed;
42勘 1:49 for the Mighty One has done great things for me, and holy is his name.
42勘 1:50 His mercy is for those who fear him from generation to generation.
42勘 1:51 He has shown strength with his arm; he has scattered the proud in the thoughts of their hearts.
42勘 1:52 He has brought down the powerful from their thrones, and lifted up the lowly;
42勘 1:53 he has filled the hungry with good things, and sent the rich away empty.
42勘 1:54 He has helped his servant Israel, in remembrance of his mercy,
42勘 1:55 according to the promise he made to our ancestors, to Abraham and to his descendants forever."
42勘 1:56 And Mary remained with her about three months and then returned to her home.
42勘 1:57 Now the time came for Elizabeth to give birth, and she bore a son.
42勘 1:58 Her neighbors and relatives heard that the Lord had shown his great mercy to her, and they rejoiced with her.
42勘 1:59 On the eighth day they came to circumcise the child, and they were going to name him Zechariah after his father.
42勘 1:60 But his mother said, "No; he is to be called John."
42勘 1:61 They said to her, "None of your relatives has this name."
42勘 1:62 Then they began motioning to his father to find out what name he wanted to give him.
42勘 1:63 He asked for a writing tablet and wrote, "His name is John." And all of them were amazed.
42勘 1:64 Immediately his mouth was opened and his tongue freed, and he began to speak, praising God.
42勘 1:65 Fear came over all their neighbors, and all these things were talked about throughout the entire hill country of Judea.
42勘 1:66 All who heard them pondered them and said, "What then will this child become?" For, indeed, the hand of the Lord was with him.
42勘 1:67 Then his father Zechariah was filled with the Holy Spirit and spoke this prophecy:
42勘 1:68 "Blessed be the Lord God of Israel, for he has looked favorably on his people and redeemed them.
42勘 1:69 He has raised up a mighty savior for us in the house of his servant David,
42勘 1:70 as he spoke through the mouth of his holy prophets from of old,
42勘 1:71 that we would be saved from our enemies and from the hand of all who hate us.
42勘 1:72 Thus he has shown the mercy promised to our ancestors, and has remembered his holy covenant,
42勘 1:73 the oath that he swore to our ancestor Abraham, to grant us
42勘 1:74 that we, being rescued from the hands of our enemies, might serve him without fear,
42勘 1:75 in holiness and righteousness before him all our days.
42勘 1:76 And you, child, will be called the prophet of the Most High; for you will go before the Lord to prepare his ways,
42勘 1:77 to give knowledge of salvation to his people by the forgiveness of their sins.
42勘 1:78 By the tender mercy of our God, the dawn from on high will break upon us,
42勘 1:79 to give light to those who sit in darkness and in the shadow of death, to guide our feet into the way of peace."
42勘 1:80 The child grew and became strong in spirit, and he was in the wilderness until the day he appeared publicly to Israel.
42勘 2:1 In those days a decree went out from Emperor Augustus that all the world should be registered.
42勘 2:2 This was the first registration and was taken while Quirinius was governor of Syria.
42勘 2:3 All went to their own towns to be registered.
42勘 2:4 Joseph also went from the town of Nazareth in Galilee to Judea, to the city of David called Bethlehem, because he was descended from the house and family of David.
42勘 2:5 He went to be registered with Mary, to whom he was engaged and who was expecting a child.
42勘 2:6 While they were there, the time came for her to deliver her child.
42勘 2:7 And she gave birth to her firstborn son and wrapped him in bands of cloth, and laid him in a manger, because there was no place for them in the inn.
42勘 2:8 In that region there were shepherds living in the fields, keeping watch over their flock by night.
42勘 2:9 Then an angel of the Lord stood before them, and the glory of the Lord shone around them, and they were terrified.
42勘 2:10 But the angel said to them, "Do not be afraid; for see--I am bringing you good news of great joy for all the people:
42勘 2:11 to you is born this day in the city of David a Savior, who is the Messiah, the Lord.
42勘 2:12 This will be a sign for you: you will find a child wrapped in bands of cloth and lying in a manger."
42勘 2:13 And suddenly there was with the angel a multitude of the heavenly host, praising God and saying,
42勘 2:14 "Glory to God in the highest heaven, and on earth peace among those whom he favors!"
42勘 2:15 When the angels had left them and gone into heaven, the shepherds said to one another, "Let us go now to Bethlehem and see this thing that has taken place, which the Lord has made known to us."
42勘 2:16 So they went with haste and found Mary and Joseph, and the child lying in the manger.
42勘 2:17 When they saw this, they made known what had been told them about this child;
42勘 2:18 and all who heard it were amazed at what the shepherds told them.
42勘 2:19 But Mary treasured all these words and pondered them in her heart.
42勘 2:20 The shepherds returned, glorifying and praising God for all they had heard and seen, as it had been told them.
42勘 2:21 After eight days had passed, it was time to circumcise the child; and he was called Jesus, the name given by the angel before he was conceived in the womb.
42勘 2:22 When the time came for their purification according to the law of Moses, they brought him up to Jerusalem to present him to the Lord
42勘 2:23 (as it is written in the law of the Lord, "Every firstborn male shall be designated as holy to the Lord"),
42勘 2:24 and they offered a sacrifice according to what is stated in the law of the Lord, "a pair of turtledoves or two young pigeons."
42勘 2:25 Now there was a man in Jerusalem whose name was Simeon; this man was righteous and devout, looking forward to the consolation of Israel, and the Holy Spirit rested on him.
42勘 2:26 It had been revealed to him by the Holy Spirit that he would not see death before he had seen the Lord's Messiah.
42勘 2:27 Guided by the Spirit, Simeon came into the temple; and when the parents brought in the child Jesus, to do for him what was customary under the law,
42勘 2:28 Simeon took him in his arms and praised God, saying,
42勘 2:29 "Master, now you are dismissing your servant in peace, according to your word;
42勘 2:30 for my eyes have seen your salvation,
42勘 2:31 which you have prepared in the presence of all peoples,
42勘 2:32 a light for revelation to the Gentiles and for glory to your people Israel."
42勘 2:33 And the child's father and mother were amazed at what was being said about him.
42勘 2:34 Then Simeon blessed them and said to his mother Mary, "This child is destined for the falling and the rising of many in Israel, and to be a sign that will be opposed
42勘 2:35 so that the inner thoughts of many will be revealed--and a sword will pierce your own soul too."
42勘 2:36 There was also a prophet, Anna the daughter of Phanuel, of the tribe of Asher. She was of a great age, having lived with her husband seven years after her marriage,
42勘 2:37 then as a widow to the age of eighty-four. She never left the temple but worshiped there with fasting and prayer night and day.
42勘 2:38 At that moment she came, and began to praise God and to speak about the child to all who were looking for the redemption of Jerusalem.
42勘 2:39 When they had finished everything required by the law of the Lord, they returned to Galilee, to their own town of Nazareth.
42勘 2:40 The child grew and became strong, filled with wisdom; and the favor of God was upon him.
42勘 2:41 Now every year his parents went to Jerusalem for the festival of the Passover.
42勘 2:42 And when he was twelve years old, they went up as usual for the festival.
42勘 2:43 When the festival was ended and they started to return, the boy Jesus stayed behind in Jerusalem, but his parents did not know it.
42勘 2:44 Assuming that he was in the group of travelers, they went a day's journey. Then they started to look for him among their relatives and friends.
42勘 2:45 When they did not find him, they returned to Jerusalem to search for him.
42勘 2:46 After three days they found him in the temple, sitting among the teachers, listening to them and asking them questions.
42勘 2:47 And all who heard him were amazed at his understanding and his answers.
42勘 2:48 When his parents saw him they were astonished; and his mother said to him, "Child, why have you treated us like this? Look, your father and I have been searching for you in great anxiety."
42勘 2:49 He said to them, "Why were you searching for me? Did you not know that I must be in my Father's house?"
42勘 2:50 But they did not understand what he said to them.
42勘 2:51 Then he went down with them and came to Nazareth, and was obedient to them. His mother treasured all these things in her heart.
42勘 2:52 And Jesus increased in wisdom and in years, and in divine and human favor.
42勘 3:1 In the fifteenth year of the reign of Emperor Tiberius, when Pontius Pilate was governor of Judea, and Herod was ruler of Galilee, and his brother Philip ruler of the region of Ituraea and Trachonitis, and Lysanias ruler of Abilene,
42勘 3:2 during the high priesthood of Annas and Caiaphas, the word of God came to John son of Zechariah in the wilderness.
42勘 3:3 He went into all the region around the Jordan, proclaiming a baptism of repentance for the forgiveness of sins,
42勘 3:4 as it is written in the book of the words of the prophet Isaiah, "The voice of one crying out in the wilderness: 'Prepare the way of the Lord, make his paths straight.
42勘 3:5 Every valley shall be filled, and every mountain and hill shall be made low, and the crooked shall be made straight, and the rough ways made smooth;
42勘 3:6 and all flesh shall see the salvation of God.'"
42勘 3:7 John said to the crowds that came out to be baptized by him, "You brood of vipers! Who warned you to flee from the wrath to come?
42勘 3:8 Bear fruits worthy of repentance. Do not begin to say to yourselves, 'We have Abraham as our ancestor'; for I tell you, God is able from these stones to raise up children to Abraham.
42勘 3:9 Even now the ax is lying at the root of the trees; every tree therefore that does not bear good fruit is cut down and thrown into the fire."
42勘 3:10 And the crowds asked him, "What then should we do?"
42勘 3:11 In reply he said to them, "Whoever has two coats must share with anyone who has none; and whoever has food must do likewise."
42勘 3:12 Even tax collectors came to be baptized, and they asked him, "Teacher, what should we do?"
42勘 3:13 He said to them, "Collect no more than the amount prescribed for you."
42勘 3:14 Soldiers also asked him, "And we, what should we do?" He said to them, "Do not extort money from anyone by threats or false accusation, and be satisfied with your wages."
42勘 3:15 As the people were filled with expectation, and all were questioning in their hearts concerning John, whether he might be the Messiah,
42勘 3:16 John answered all of them by saying, "I baptize you with water; but one who is more powerful than I is coming; I am not worthy to untie the thong of his sandals. He will baptize you with the Holy Spirit and fire.
42勘 3:17 His winnowing fork is in his hand, to clear his threshing floor and to gather the wheat into his granary; but the chaff he will burn with unquenchable fire."
42勘 3:18 So, with many other exhortations, he proclaimed the good news to the people.
42勘 3:19 But Herod the ruler, who had been rebuked by him because of Herodias, his brother's wife, and because of all the evil things that Herod had done,
42勘 3:20 added to them all by shutting up John in prison.
42勘 3:21 Now when all the people were baptized, and when Jesus also had been baptized and was praying, the heaven was opened,
42勘 3:22 and the Holy Spirit descended upon him in bodily form like a dove. And a voice came from heaven, "You are my Son, the Beloved; with you I am well pleased."
42勘 3:23 Jesus was about thirty years old when he began his work. He was the son (as was thought) of Joseph son of Heli,
42勘 3:24 son of Matthat, son of Levi, son of Melchi, son of Jannai, son of Joseph,
42勘 3:25 son of Mattathias, son of Amos, son of Nahum, son of Esli, son of Naggai,
42勘 3:26 son of Maath, son of Mattathias, son of Semein, son of Josech, son of Joda,
42勘 3:27 son of Joanan, son of Rhesa, son of Zerubbabel, son of Shealtiel, son of Neri,
42勘 3:28 son of Melchi, son of Addi, son of Cosam, son of Elmadam, son of Er,
42勘 3:29 son of Joshua, son of Eliezer, son of Jorim, son of Matthat, son of Levi,
42勘 3:30 son of Simeon, son of Judah, son of Joseph, son of Jonam, son of Eliakim,
42勘 3:31 son of Melea, son of Menna, son of Mattatha, son of Nathan, son of David,
42勘 3:32 son of Jesse, son of Obed, son of Boaz, son of Sala, son of Nahshon,
42勘 3:33 son of Amminadab, son of Admin, son of Arni, son of Hezron, son of Perez, son of Judah,
42勘 3:34 son of Jacob, son of Isaac, son of Abraham, son of Terah, son of Nahor,
42勘 3:35 son of Serug, son of Reu, son of Peleg, son of Eber, son of Shelah,
42勘 3:36 son of Cainan, son of Arphaxad, son of Shem, son of Noah, son of Lamech,
42勘 3:37 son of Methuselah, son of Enoch, son of Jared, son of Mahalaleel, son of Cainan,
42勘 3:38 son of Enos, son of Seth, son of Adam, son of God.
42勘 4:1 Jesus, full of the Holy Spirit, returned from the Jordan and was led by the Spirit in the wilderness,
42勘 4:2 where for forty days he was tempted by the devil. He ate nothing at all during those days, and when they were over, he was famished.
42勘 4:3 The devil said to him, "If you are the Son of God, command this stone to become a loaf of bread."
42勘 4:4 Jesus answered him, 'It is written, 'One does not live by bread alone.'"
42勘 4:5 Then the devil led him up and showed him in an instant all the kingdoms of the world.
42勘 4:6 And the devil said to him, "To you I will give their glory and all this authority; for it has been given over to me, and I give it to anyone I please.
42勘 4:7 If you, then, will worship me, it will all be yours."
42勘 4:8 Jesus answered him, 'It is written, 'Worship the Lord your God, and serve only him.'"
42勘 4:9 Then the devil took him to Jerusalem, and placed him on the pinnacle of the temple, saying to him, "If you are the Son of God, throw yourself down from here,
42勘 4:10 for it is written, 'He will command his angels concerning you, to protect you,'
42勘 4:11 and 'On their hands they will bear you up, so that you will not dash your foot against a stone.'"
42勘 4:12 Jesus answered him, 'It is said, 'Do not put the Lord your God to the test.'"
42勘 4:13 When the devil had finished every test, he departed from him until an opportune time.
42勘 4:14 Then Jesus, filled with the power of the Spirit, returned to Galilee, and a report about him spread through all the surrounding country.
42勘 4:15 He began to teach in their synagogues and was praised by everyone.
42勘 4:16 When he came to Nazareth, where he had been brought up, he went to the synagogue on the sabbath day, as was his custom. He stood up to read,
42勘 4:17 and the scroll of the prophet Isaiah was given to him. He unrolled the scroll and found the place where it was written:
42勘 4:18 'The Spirit of the Lord is upon me, because he has anointed me to bring good news to the poor. He has sent me to proclaim release to the captives and recovery of sight to the blind, to let the oppressed go free,
42勘 4:19 to proclaim the year of the Lord's favor."
42勘 4:20 And he rolled up the scroll, gave it back to the attendant, and sat down. The eyes of all in the synagogue were fixed on him.
42勘 4:21 Then he began to say to them, "Today this scripture has been fulfilled in your hearing."
42勘 4:22 All spoke well of him and were amazed at the gracious words that came from his mouth. They said, "Is not this Joseph's son?"
42勘 4:23 He said to them, "Doubtless you will quote to me this proverb, 'Doctor, cure yourself!' And you will say, 'Do here also in your hometown the things that we have heard you did at Capernaum.'"
42勘 4:24 And he said, "Truly I tell you, no prophet is accepted in the prophet's hometown.
42勘 4:25 But the truth is, there were many widows in Israel in the time of Elijah, when the heaven was shut up three years and six months, and there was a severe famine over all the land;
42勘 4:26 yet Elijah was sent to none of them except to a widow at Zarephath in Sidon.
42勘 4:27 There were also many lepers in Israel in the time of the prophet Elisha, and none of them was cleansed except Naaman the Syrian."
42勘 4:28 When they heard this, all in the synagogue were filled with rage.
42勘 4:29 They got up, drove him out of the town, and led him to the brow of the hill on which their town was built, so that they might hurl him off the cliff.
42勘 4:30 But he passed through the midst of them and went on his way.
42勘 4:31 He went down to Capernaum, a city in Galilee, and was teaching them on the sabbath.
42勘 4:32 They were astounded at his teaching, because he spoke with authority.
42勘 4:33 In the synagogue there was a man who had the spirit of an unclean demon, and he cried out with a loud voice,
42勘 4:34 "Let us alone! What have you to do with us, Jesus of Nazareth? Have you come to destroy us? I know who you are, the Holy One of God."
42勘 4:35 But Jesus rebuked him, saying, "Be silent, and come out of him!" When the demon had thrown him down before them, he came out of him without having done him any harm.
42勘 4:36 They were all amazed and kept saying to one another, "What kind of utterance is this? For with authority and power he commands the unclean spirits, and out they come!"
42勘 4:37 And a report about him began to reach every place in the region.
42勘 4:38 After leaving the synagogue he entered Simon's house. Now Simon's mother-in-law was suffering from a high fever, and they asked him about her.
42勘 4:39 Then he stood over her and rebuked the fever, and it left her. Immediately she got up and began to serve them.
42勘 4:40 As the sun was setting, all those who had any who were sick with various kinds of diseases brought them to him; and he laid his hands on each of them and cured them.
42勘 4:41 Demons also came out of many, shouting, "You are the Son of God!" But he rebuked them and would not allow them to speak, because they knew that he was the Messiah.
42勘 4:42 At daybreak he departed and went into a deserted place. And the crowds were looking for him; and when they reached him, they wanted to prevent him from leaving them.
42勘 4:43 But he said to them, "I must proclaim the good news of the kingdom of God to the other cities also; for I was sent for this purpose."
42勘 4:44 So he continued proclaiming the message in the synagogues of Judea.
42勘 5:1 Once while Jesus was standing beside the lake of Gennesaret, and the crowd was pressing in on him to hear the word of God,
42勘 5:2 he saw two boats there at the shore of the lake; the fishermen had gone out of them and were washing their nets.
42勘 5:3 He got into one of the boats, the one belonging to Simon, and asked him to put out a little way from the shore. Then he sat down and taught the crowds from the boat.
42勘 5:4 When he had finished speaking, he said to Simon, "Put out into the deep water and let down your nets for a catch."
42勘 5:5 Simon answered, "Master, we have worked all night long but have caught nothing. Yet if you say so, I will let down the nets."
42勘 5:6 When they had done this, they caught so many fish that their nets were beginning to break.
42勘 5:7 So they signaled their partners in the other boat to come and help them. And they came and filled both boats, so that they began to sink.
42勘 5:8 But when Simon Peter saw it, he fell down at Jesus' knees, saying, "Go away from me, Lord, for I am a sinful man!"
42勘 5:9 For he and all who were with him were amazed at the catch of fish that they had taken;
42勘 5:10 and so also were James and John, sons of Zebedee, who were partners with Simon. Then Jesus said to Simon, "Do not be afraid; from now on you will be catching people."
42勘 5:11 When they had brought their boats to shore, they left everything and followed him.
42勘 5:12 Once, when he was in one of the cities, there was a man covered with leprosy. When he saw Jesus, he bowed with his face to the ground and begged him, "Lord, if you choose, you can make me clean."
42勘 5:13 Then Jesus stretched out his hand, touched him, and said, "I do choose. Be made clean." Immediately the leprosy left him.
42勘 5:14 And he ordered him to tell no one. "Go," he said, "and show yourself to the priest, and, as Moses commanded, make an offering for your cleansing, for a testimony to them."
42勘 5:15 But now more than ever the word about Jesus spread abroad; many crowds would gather to hear him and to be cured of their diseases.
42勘 5:16 But he would withdraw to deserted places and pray.
42勘 5:17 One day, while he was teaching, Pharisees and teachers of the law were sitting near by (they had come from every village of Galilee and Judea and from Jerusalem); and the power of the Lord was with him to heal.
42勘 5:18 Just then some men came, carrying a paralyzed man on a bed. They were trying to bring him in and lay him before Jesus;
42勘 5:19 but finding no way to bring him in because of the crowd, they went up on the roof and let him down with his bed through the tiles into the middle of the crowd in front of Jesus.
42勘 5:20 When he saw their faith, he said, "Friend, your sins are forgiven you."
42勘 5:21 Then the scribes and the Pharisees began to question, "Who is this who is speaking blasphemies? Who can forgive sins but God alone?"
42勘 5:22 When Jesus perceived their questionings, he answered them, "Why do you raise such questions in your hearts?
42勘 5:23 Which is easier, to say, 'Your sins are forgiven you,' or to say, 'Stand up and walk'?
42勘 5:24 But so that you may know that the Son of Man has authority on earth to forgive sins"--he said to the one who was paralyzed--"I say to you, stand up and take your bed and go to your home."
42勘 5:25 Immediately he stood up before them, took what he had been lying on, and went to his home, glorifying God.
42勘 5:26 Amazement seized all of them, and they glorified God and were filled with awe, saying, "We have seen strange things today."
42勘 5:27 After this he went out and saw a tax collector named Levi, sitting at the tax booth; and he said to him, "Follow me."
42勘 5:28 And he got up, left everything, and followed him.
42勘 5:29 Then Levi gave a great banquet for him in his house; and there was a large crowd of tax collectors and others sitting at the table with them.
42勘 5:30 The Pharisees and their scribes were complaining to his disciples, saying, "Why do you eat and drink with tax collectors and sinners?"
42勘 5:31 Jesus answered, "Those who are well have no need of a physician, but those who are sick;
42勘 5:32 I have come to call not the righteous but sinners to repentance."
42勘 5:33 Then they said to him, "John's disciples, like the disciples of the Pharisees, frequently fast and pray, but your disciples eat and drink.
42勘 5:34 Jesus said to them, "You cannot make wedding guests fast while the bridegroom is with them, can you?
42勘 5:35 The days will come when the bridegroom will be taken away from them, and then they will fast in those days."
42勘 5:36 He also told them a parable: "No one tears a piece from a new garment and sews it on an old garment; otherwise the new will be torn, and the piece from the new will not match the old.
42勘 5:37 And no one puts new wine into old wineskins; otherwise the new wine will burst the skins and will be spilled, and the skins will be destroyed.
42勘 5:38 But new wine must be put into fresh wineskins.
42勘 5:39 And no one after drinking old wine desires new wine, but says, 'The old is good.'"
42勘 6:1 One sabbath while Jesus was going through the grainfields, his disciples plucked some heads of grain, rubbed them in their hands, and ate them.
42勘 6:2 But some of the Pharisees said, "Why are you doing what is not lawful on the sabbath?"
42勘 6:3 Jesus answered, "Have you not read what David did when he and his companions were hungry?
42勘 6:4 He entered the house of God and took and ate the bread of the Presence, which it is not lawful for any but the priests to eat, and gave some to his companions?"
42勘 6:5 Then he said to them, "The Son of Man is lord of the sabbath."
42勘 6:6 On another sabbath he entered the synagogue and taught, and there was a man there whose right hand was withered.
42勘 6:7 The scribes and the Pharisees watched him to see whether he would cure on the sabbath, so that they might find an accusation against him.
42勘 6:8 Even though he knew what they were thinking, he said to the man who had the withered hand, "Come and stand here." He got up and stood there.
42勘 6:9 Then Jesus said to them, "I ask you, is it lawful to do good or to do harm on the sabbath, to save life or to destroy it?"
42勘 6:10 After looking around at all of them, he said to him, "Stretch out your hand." He did so, and his hand was restored.
42勘 6:11 But they were filled with fury and discussed with one another what they might do to Jesus.
42勘 6:12 Now during those days he went out to the mountain to pray; and he spent the night in prayer to God.
42勘 6:13 And when day came, he called his disciples and chose twelve of them, whom he also named apostles:
42勘 6:14 Simon, whom he named Peter, and his brother Andrew, and James, and John, and Philip, and Bartholomew,
42勘 6:15 and Matthew, and Thomas, and James son of Alphaeus, and Simon, who was called the Zealot,
42勘 6:16 and Judas son of James, and Judas Iscariot, who became a traitor.
42勘 6:17 He came down with them and stood on a level place, with a great crowd of his disciples and a great multitude of people from all Judea, Jerusalem, and the coast of Tyre and Sidon.
42勘 6:18 They had come to hear him and to be healed of their diseases; and those who were troubled with unclean spirits were cured.
42勘 6:19 And all in the crowd were trying to touch him, for power came out from him and healed all of them.
42勘 6:20 Then he looked up at his disciples and said: "Blessed are you who are poor, for yours is the kingdom of God.
42勘 6:21 "Blessed are you who are hungry now, for you will be filled. "Blessed are you who weep now, for you will laugh.
42勘 6:22 "Blessed are you when people hate you, and when they exclude you, revile you, and defame you on account of the Son of Man.
42勘 6:23 Rejoice in that day and leap for joy, for surely your reward is great in heaven; for that is what their ancestors did to the prophets.
42勘 6:24 "But woe to you who are rich, for you have received your consolation.
42勘 6:25 "Woe to you who are full now, for you will be hungry. "Woe to you who are laughing now, for you will mourn and weep.
42勘 6:26 "Woe to you when all speak well of you, for that is what their ancestors did to the false prophets.
42勘 6:27 "But I say to you that listen, Love your enemies, do good to those who hate you,
42勘 6:28 bless those who curse you, pray for those who abuse you.
42勘 6:29 If anyone strikes you on the cheek, offer the other also; and from anyone who takes away your coat do not withhold even your shirt.
42勘 6:30 Give to everyone who begs from you; and if anyone takes away your goods, do not ask for them again.
42勘 6:31 Do to others as you would have them do to you.
42勘 6:32 "If you love those who love you, what credit is that to you? For even sinners love those who love them.
42勘 6:33 If you do good to those who do good to you, what credit is that to you? For even sinners do the same.
42勘 6:34 If you lend to those from whom you hope to receive, what credit is that to you? Even sinners lend to sinners, to receive as much again.
42勘 6:35 But love your enemies, do good, and lend, expecting nothing in return. Your reward will be great, and you will be children of the Most High; for he is kind to the ungrateful and the wicked.
42勘 6:36 Be merciful, just as your Father is merciful.
42勘 6:37 "Do not judge, and you will not be judged; do not condemn, and you will not be condemned. Forgive, and you will be forgiven;
42勘 6:38 give, and it will be given to you. A good measure, pressed down, shaken together, running over, will be put into your lap; for the measure you give will be the measure you get back."
42勘 6:39 He also told them a parable: "Can a blind person guide a blind person? Will not both fall into a pit?
42勘 6:40 A disciple is not above the teacher, but everyone who is fully qualified will be like the teacher.
42勘 6:41 Why do you see the speck in your neighbor's eye, but do not notice the log in your own eye?
42勘 6:42 Or how can you say to your neighbor, 'Friend, let me take out the speck in your eye,' when you yourself do not see the log in your own eye? You hypocrite, first take the log out of your own eye, and then you will see clearly to take the speck out of your neighbor's eye.
42勘 6:43 "No good tree bears bad fruit, nor again does a bad tree bear good fruit;
42勘 6:44 for each tree is known by its own fruit. Figs are not gathered from thorns, nor are grapes picked from a bramble bush.
42勘 6:45 The good person out of the good treasure of the heart produces good, and the evil person out of evil treasure produces evil; for it is out of the abundance of the heart that the mouth speaks.
42勘 6:46 "Why do you call me 'Lord, Lord,' and do not do what I tell you?
42勘 6:47 I will show you what someone is like who comes to me, hears my words, and acts on them.
42勘 6:48 That one is like a man building a house, who dug deeply and laid the foundation on rock; when a flood arose, the river burst against that house but could not shake it, because it had been well built.
42勘 6:49 But the one who hears and does not act is like a man who built a house on the ground without a foundation. When the river burst against it, immediately it fell, and great was the ruin of that house."
42勘 7:1 After Jesus had finished all his sayings in the hearing of the people, he entered Capernaum.
42勘 7:2 A centurion there had a slave whom he valued highly, and who was ill and close to death.
42勘 7:3 When he heard about Jesus, he sent some Jewish elders to him, asking him to come and heal his slave.
42勘 7:4 When they came to Jesus, they appealed to him earnestly, saying, "He is worthy of having you do this for him,
42勘 7:5 for he loves our people, and it is he who built our synagogue for us."
42勘 7:6 And Jesus went with them, but when he was not far from the house, the centurion sent friends to say to him, "Lord, do not trouble yourself, for I am not worthy to have you come under my roof;
42勘 7:7 therefore I did not presume to come to you. But only speak the word, and let my servant be healed.
42勘 7:8 For I also am a man set under authority, with soldiers under me; and I say to one, 'Go,' and he goes, and to another, 'Come,' and he comes, and to my slave, 'Do this,' and the slave does it."
42勘 7:9 When Jesus heard this he was amazed at him, and turning to the crowd that followed him, he said, "I tell you, not even in Israel have I found such faith."
42勘 7:10 When those who had been sent returned to the house, they found the slave in good health.
42勘 7:11 Soon afterwards he went to a town called Nain, and his disciples and a large crowd went with him.
42勘 7:12 As he approached the gate of the town, a man who had died was being carried out. He was his mother's only son, and she was a widow; and with her was a large crowd from the town.
42勘 7:13 When the Lord saw her, he had compassion for her and said to her, "Do not weep."
42勘 7:14 Then he came forward and touched the bier, and the bearers stood still. And he said, "Young man, I say to you, rise!"
42勘 7:15 The dead man sat up and began to speak, and Jesus gave him to his mother.
42勘 7:16 Fear seized all of them; and they glorified God, saying, "A great prophet has risen among us!" and "God has looked favorably on his people!"
42勘 7:17 This word about him spread throughout Judea and all the surrounding country.
42勘 7:18 The disciples of John reported all these things to him. So John summoned two of his disciples
42勘 7:19 and sent them to the Lord to ask, "Are you the one who is to come, or are we to wait for another?"
42勘 7:20 When the men had come to him, they said, "John the Baptist has sent us to you to ask, 'Are you the one who is to come, or are we to wait for another?'"
42勘 7:21 Jesus had just then cured many people of diseases, plagues, and evil spirits, and had given sight to many who were blind.
42勘 7:22 And he answered them, "Go and tell John what you have seen and heard: the blind receive their sight, the lame walk, the lepers are cleansed, the deaf hear, the dead are raised, the poor have good news brought to them.
42勘 7:23 And blessed is anyone who takes no offense at me."
42勘 7:24 When John's messengers had gone, Jesus began to speak to the crowds about John: "What did you go out into the wilderness to look at? A reed shaken by the wind?
42勘 7:25 What then did you go out to see? Someone dressed in soft robes? Look, those who put on fine clothing and live in luxury are in royal palaces.
42勘 7:26 What then did you go out to see? A prophet? Yes, I tell you, and more than a prophet.
42勘 7:27 This is the one about whom it is written, 'See, I am sending my messenger ahead of you, who will prepare your way before you.'
42勘 7:28 I tell you, among those born of women no one is greater than John; yet the least in the kingdom of God is greater than he."
42勘 7:29 (And all the people who heard this, including the tax collectors, acknowledged the justice of God, because they had been baptized with John's baptism.
42勘 7:30 But by refusing to be baptized by him, the Pharisees and the lawyers rejected God's purpose for themselves.)
42勘 7:31 "To what then will I compare the people of this generation, and what are they like?
42勘 7:32 They are like children sitting in the marketplace and calling to one another, 'We played the flute for you, and you did not dance; we wailed, and you did not weep.'
42勘 7:33 For John the Baptist has come eating no bread and drinking no wine, and you say, 'He has a demon';
42勘 7:34 the Son of Man has come eating and drinking, and you say, 'Look, a glutton and a drunkard, a friend of tax collectors and sinners!'
42勘 7:35 Nevertheless, wisdom is vindicated by all her children."
42勘 7:36 One of the Pharisees asked Jesus to eat with him, and he went into the Pharisee's house and took his place at the table.
42勘 7:37 And a woman in the city, who was a sinner, having learned that he was eating in the Pharisee's house, brought an alabaster jar of ointment.
42勘 7:38 She stood behind him at his feet, weeping, and began to bathe his feet with her tears and to dry them with her hair. Then she continued kissing his feet and anointing them with the ointment.
42勘 7:39 Now when the Pharisee who had invited him saw it, he said to himself, "If this man were a prophet, he would have known who and what kind of woman this is who is touching him--that she is a sinner."
42勘 7:40 Jesus spoke up and said to him, "Simon, I have something to say to you." "Teacher," he replied, "Speak."
42勘 7:41 "A certain creditor had two debtors; one owed five hundred denarii, and the other fifty.
42勘 7:42 When they could not pay, he canceled the debts for both of them. Now which of them will love him more?"
42勘 7:43 Simon answered, "I suppose the one for whom he canceled the greater debt." And Jesus said to him, "You have judged rightly."
42勘 7:44 Then turning toward the woman, he said to Simon, "Do you see this woman? I entered your house; you gave me no water for my feet, but she has bathed my feet with her tears and dried them with her hair.
42勘 7:45 You gave me no kiss, but from the time I came in she has not stopped kissing my feet.
42勘 7:46 You did not anoint my head with oil, but she has anointed my feet with ointment.
42勘 7:47 Therefore, I tell you, her sins, which were many, have been forgiven; hence she has shown great love. But the one to whom little is forgiven, loves little."
42勘 7:48 Then he said to her, "Your sins are forgiven."
42勘 7:49 But those who were at the table with him began to say among themselves, "Who is this who even forgives sins?"
42勘 7:50 And he said to the woman, "Your faith has saved you; go in peace."
42勘 8:1 Soon afterwards he went on through cities and villages, proclaiming and bringing the good news of the kingdom of God. The twelve were with him,
42勘 8:2 as well as some women who had been cured of evil spirits and infirmities: Mary, called Magdalene, from whom seven demons had gone out,
42勘 8:3 and Joanna, the wife of Herod's steward Chuza, and Susanna, and many others, who provided for them out of their resources.
42勘 8:4 When a great crowd gathered and people from town after town came to him, he said in a parable:
42勘 8:5 "A sower went out to sow his seed; and as he sowed, some fell on the path and was trampled on, and the birds of the air ate it up.
42勘 8:6 Some fell on the rock; and as it grew up, it withered for lack of moisture.
42勘 8:7 Some fell among thorns, and the thorns grew with it and choked it.
42勘 8:8 Some fell into good soil, and when it grew, it produced a hundredfold." As he said this, he called out, "Let anyone with ears to hear listen!"
42勘 8:9 Then his disciples asked him what this parable meant.
42勘 8:10 He said, "To you it has been given to know the secrets of the kingdom of God; but to others I speak in parables, so that 'looking they may not perceive, and listening they may not understand.'
42勘 8:11 "Now the parable is this: The seed is the word of God.
42勘 8:12 The ones on the path are those who have heard; then the devil comes and takes away the word from their hearts, so that they may not believe and be saved.
42勘 8:13 The ones on the rock are those who, when they hear the word, receive it with joy. But these have no root; they believe only for a while and in a time of testing fall away.
42勘 8:14 As for what fell among the thorns, these are the ones who hear; but as they go on their way, they are choked by the cares and riches and pleasures of life, and their fruit does not mature.
42勘 8:15 But as for that in the good soil, these are the ones who, when they hear the word, hold it fast in an honest and good heart, and bear fruit with patient endurance.
42勘 8:16 "No one after lighting a lamp hides it under a jar, or puts it under a bed, but puts it on a lampstand, so that those who enter may see the light.
42勘 8:17 For nothing is hidden that will not be disclosed, nor is anything secret that will not become known and come to light.
42勘 8:18 Then pay attention to how you listen; for to those who have, more will be given; and from those who do not have, even what they seem to have will be taken away."
42勘 8:19 Then his mother and his brothers came to him, but they could not reach him because of the crowd.
42勘 8:20 And he was told, "Your mother and your brothers are standing outside, wanting to see you."
42勘 8:21 But he said to them, "My mother and my brothers are those who hear the word of God and do it."
42勘 8:22 One day he got into a boat with his disciples, and he said to them, "Let us go across to the other side of the lake." So they put out,
42勘 8:23 and while they were sailing he fell asleep. A windstorm swept down on the lake, and the boat was filling with water, and they were in danger.
42勘 8:24 They went to him and woke him up, shouting, "Master, Master, we are perishing!" And he woke up and rebuked the wind and the raging waves; they ceased, and there was a calm.
42勘 8:25 He said to them, "Where is your faith?" They were afraid and amazed, and said to one another, "Who then is this, that he commands even the winds and the water, and they obey him?"
42勘 8:26 Then they arrived at the country of the Gerasenes, which is opposite Galilee.
42勘 8:27 As he stepped out on land, a man of the city who had demons met him. For a long time he had worn no clothes, and he did not live in a house but in the tombs.
42勘 8:28 When he saw Jesus, he fell down before him and shouted at the top of his voice, "What have you to do with me, Jesus, Son of the Most High God? I beg you, do not torment me"--
42勘 8:29 for Jesus had commanded the unclean spirit to come out of the man. (For many times it had seized him; he was kept under guard and bound with chains and shackles, but he would break the bonds and be driven by the demon into the wilds.)
42勘 8:30 Jesus then asked him, "What is your name?" He said, "Legion"; for many demons had entered him.
42勘 8:31 They begged him not to order them to go back into the abyss.
42勘 8:32 Now there on the hillside a large herd of swine was feeding; and the demons begged Jesus to let them enter these. So he gave them permission.
42勘 8:33 Then the demons came out of the man and entered the swine, and the herd rushed down the steep bank into the lake and was drowned.
42勘 8:34 When the swineherds saw what had happened, they ran off and told it in the city and in the country.
42勘 8:35 Then people came out to see what had happened, and when they came to Jesus, they found the man from whom the demons had gone sitting at the feet of Jesus, clothed and in his right mind. And they were afraid.
42勘 8:36 Those who had seen it told them how the one who had been possessed by demons had been healed.
42勘 8:37 Then all the people of the surrounding country of the Gerasenes asked Jesus to leave them; for they were seized with great fear. So he got into the boat and returned.
42勘 8:38 The man from whom the demons had gone begged that he might be with him; but Jesus sent him away, saying,
42勘 8:39 "Return to your home, and declare how much God has done for you." So he went away, proclaiming throughout the city how much Jesus had done for him.
42勘 8:40 Now when Jesus returned, the crowd welcomed him, for they were all waiting for him.
42勘 8:41 Just then there came a man named Jairus, a leader of the synagogue. He fell at Jesus' feet and begged him to come to his house,
42勘 8:42 for he had an only daughter, about twelve years old, who was dying. As he went, the crowds pressed in on him.
42勘 8:43 Now there was a woman who had been suffering from hemorrhages for twelve years; and though she had spent all she had on physicians, no one could cure her.
42勘 8:44 She came up behind him and touched the fringe of his clothes, and immediately her hemorrhage stopped.
42勘 8:45 Then Jesus asked, "Who touched me?" When all denied it, Peter said, "Master, the crowds surround you and press in on you."
42勘 8:46 But Jesus said, "Someone touched me; for I noticed that power had gone out from me."
42勘 8:47 When the woman saw that she could not remain hidden, she came trembling; and falling down before him, she declared in the presence of all the people why she had touched him, and how she had been immediately healed.
42勘 8:48 He said to her, "Daughter, your faith has made you well; go in peace."
42勘 8:49 While he was still speaking, someone came from the leader's house to say, "Your daughter is dead; do not trouble the teacher any longer."
42勘 8:50 When Jesus heard this, he replied, "Do not fear. Only believe, and she will be saved."
42勘 8:51 When he came to the house, he did not allow anyone to enter with him, except Peter, John, and James, and the child's father and mother.
42勘 8:52 They were all weeping and wailing for her; but he said, "Do not weep; for she is not dead but sleeping."
42勘 8:53 And they laughed at him, knowing that she was dead.
42勘 8:54 But he took her by the hand and called out, "Child, get up!"
42勘 8:55 Her spirit returned, and she got up at once. Then he directed them to give her something to eat.
42勘 8:56 Her parents were astounded; but he ordered them to tell no one what had happened.
42勘 9:1 Then Jesus called the twelve together and gave them power and authority over all demons and to cure diseases,
42勘 9:2 and he sent them out to proclaim the kingdom of God and to heal.
42勘 9:3 He said to them, "Take nothing for your journey, no staff, nor bag, nor bread, nor money--not even an extra tunic.
42勘 9:4 Whatever house you enter, stay there, and leave from there.
42勘 9:5 Wherever they do not welcome you, as you are leaving that town shake the dust off your feet as a testimony against them."
42勘 9:6 They departed and went through the villages, bringing the good news and curing diseases everywhere.
42勘 9:7 Now Herod the ruler heard about all that had taken place, and he was perplexed, because it was said by some that John had been raised from the dead,
42勘 9:8 by some that Elijah had appeared, and by others that one of the ancient prophets had arisen.
42勘 9:9 Herod said, "John I beheaded; but who is this about whom I hear such things?" And he tried to see him.
42勘 9:10 On their return the apostles told Jesus all they had done. He took them with him and withdrew privately to a city called Bethsaida.
42勘 9:11 When the crowds found out about it, they followed him; and he welcomed them, and spoke to them about the kingdom of God, and healed those who needed to be cured.
42勘 9:12 The day was drawing to a close, and the twelve came to him and said, "Send the crowd away, so that they may go into the surrounding villages and countryside, to lodge and get provisions; for we are here in a deserted place."
42勘 9:13 But he said to them, "You give them something to eat." They said, "We have no more than five loaves and two fish--unless we are to go and buy food for all these people."
42勘 9:14 For there were about five thousand men. And he said to his disciples, "Make them sit down in groups of about fifty each."
42勘 9:15 They did so and made them all sit down.
42勘 9:16 And taking the five loaves and the two fish, he looked up to heaven, and blessed and broke them, and gave them to the disciples to set before the crowd.
42勘 9:17 And all ate and were filled. What was left over was gathered up, twelve baskets of broken pieces.
42勘 9:18 Once when Jesus was praying alone, with only the disciples near him, he asked them, "Who do the crowds say that I am?"
42勘 9:19 They answered, "John the Baptist; but others, Elijah; and still others, that one of the ancient prophets has arisen."
42勘 9:20 He said to them, "But who do you say that I am?" Peter answered, "The Messiah of God."
42勘 9:21 He sternly ordered and commanded them not to tell anyone,
42勘 9:22 saying, "The Son of Man must undergo great suffering, and be rejected by the elders, chief priests, and scribes, and be killed, and on the third day be raised."
42勘 9:23 Then he said to them all, "If any want to become my followers, let them deny themselves and take up their cross daily and follow me.
42勘 9:24 For those who want to save their life will lose it, and those who lose their life for my sake will save it.
42勘 9:25 What does it profit them if they gain the whole world, but lose or forfeit themselves?
42勘 9:26 Those who are ashamed of me and of my words, of them the Son of Man will be ashamed when he comes in his glory and the glory of the Father and of the holy angels.
42勘 9:27 But truly I tell you, there are some standing here who will not taste death before they see the kingdom of God."
42勘 9:28 Now about eight days after these sayings Jesus took with him Peter and John and James, and went up on the mountain to pray.
42勘 9:29 And while he was praying, the appearance of his face changed, and his clothes became dazzling white.
42勘 9:30 Suddenly they saw two men, Moses and Elijah, talking to him.
42勘 9:31 They appeared in glory and were speaking of his departure, which he was about to accomplish at Jerusalem.
42勘 9:32 Now Peter and his companions were weighed down with sleep; but since they had stayed awake, they saw his glory and the two men who stood with him.
42勘 9:33 Just as they were leaving him, Peter said to Jesus, "Master, it is good for us to be here; let us make three dwellings, one for you, one for Moses, and one for Elijah"--not knowing what he said.
42勘 9:34 While he was saying this, a cloud came and overshadowed them; and they were terrified as they entered the cloud.
42勘 9:35 Then from the cloud came a voice that said, "This is my Son, my Chosen; listen to him!"
42勘 9:36 When the voice had spoken, Jesus was found alone. And they kept silent and in those days told no one any of the things they had seen.
42勘 9:37 On the next day, when they had come down from the mountain, a great crowd met him.
42勘 9:38 Just then a man from the crowd shouted, "Teacher, I beg you to look at my son; he is my only child.
42勘 9:39 Suddenly a spirit seizes him, and all at once he shrieks. It convulses him until he foams at the mouth; it mauls him and will scarcely leave him.
42勘 9:40 I begged your disciples to cast it out, but they could not."
42勘 9:41 Jesus answered, "You faithless and perverse generation, how much longer must I be with you and bear with you? Bring your son here."
42勘 9:42 While he was coming, the demon dashed him to the ground in convulsions. But Jesus rebuked the unclean spirit, healed the boy, and gave him back to his father.
42勘 9:43 And all were astounded at the greatness of God. While everyone was amazed at all that he was doing, he said to his disciples,
42勘 9:44 "Let these words sink into your ears: The Son of Man is going to be betrayed into human hands."
42勘 9:45 But they did not understand this saying; its meaning was concealed from them, so that they could not perceive it. And they were afraid to ask him about this saying.
42勘 9:46 An argument arose among them as to which one of them was the greatest.
42勘 9:47 But Jesus, aware of their inner thoughts, took a little child and put it by his side,
42勘 9:48 and said to them, "Whoever welcomes this child in my name welcomes me, and whoever welcomes me welcomes the one who sent me; for the least among all of you is the greatest."
42勘 9:49 John answered, "Master, we saw someone casting out demons in your name, and we tried to stop him, because he does not follow with us."
42勘 9:50 But Jesus said to him, "Do not stop him; for whoever is not against you is for you."
42勘 9:51 When the days drew near for him to be taken up, he set his face to go to Jerusalem.
42勘 9:52 And he sent messengers ahead of him. On their way they entered a village of the Samaritans to make ready for him;
42勘 9:53 but they did not receive him, because his face was set toward Jerusalem.
42勘 9:54 When his disciples James and John saw it, they said, "Lord, do you want us to command fire to come down from heaven and consume them?"
42勘 9:55 But he turned and rebuked them.
42勘 9:56 Then they went on to another village.
42勘 9:57 As they were going along the road, someone said to him, "I will follow you wherever you go."
42勘 9:58 And Jesus said to him, "Foxes have holes, and birds of the air have nests; but the Son of Man has nowhere to lay his head."
42勘 9:59 To another he said, "Follow me." But he said, "Lord, first let me go and bury my father."
42勘 9:60 But Jesus said to him, "Let the dead bury their own dead; but as for you, go and proclaim the kingdom of God."
42勘 9:61 Another said, "I will follow you, Lord; but let me first say farewell to those at my home."
42勘 9:62 Jesus said to him, "No one who puts a hand to the plow and looks back is fit for the kingdom of God."
42勘 10:1 After this the Lord appointed seventy others and sent them on ahead of him in pairs to every town and place where he himself intended to go.
42勘 10:2 He said to them, "The harvest is plentiful, but the laborers are few; therefore ask the Lord of the harvest to send out laborers into his harvest.
42勘 10:3 Go on your way. See, I am sending you out like lambs into the midst of wolves.
42勘 10:4 Carry no purse, no bag, no sandals; and greet no one on the road.
42勘 10:5 Whatever house you enter, first say, 'Peace to this house!'
42勘 10:6 And if anyone is there who shares in peace, your peace will rest on that person; but if not, it will return to you.
42勘 10:7 Remain in the same house, eating and drinking whatever they provide, for the laborer deserves to be paid. Do not move about from house to house.
42勘 10:8 Whenever you enter a town and its people welcome you, eat what is set before you;
42勘 10:9 cure the sick who are there, and say to them, 'The kingdom of God has come near to you.'
42勘 10:10 But whenever you enter a town and they do not welcome you, go out into its streets and say,
42勘 10:11 'Even the dust of your town that clings to our feet, we wipe off in protest against you. Yet know this: the kingdom of God has come near.'
42勘 10:12 I tell you, on that day it will be more tolerable for Sodom than for that town.
42勘 10:13 "Woe to you, Chorazin! Woe to you, Bethsaida! For if the deeds of power done in you had been done in Tyre and Sidon, they would have repented long ago, sitting in sackcloth and ashes.
42勘 10:14 But at the judgment it will be more tolerable for Tyre and Sidon than for you.
42勘 10:15 And you, Capernaum, will you be exalted to heaven? No, you will be brought down to Hades.
42勘 10:16 "Whoever listens to you listens to me, and whoever rejects you rejects me, and whoever rejects me rejects the one who sent me."
42勘 10:17 The seventy returned with joy, saying, "Lord, in your name even the demons submit to us!"
42勘 10:18 He said to them, "I watched Satan fall from heaven like a flash of lightning.
42勘 10:19 See, I have given you authority to tread on snakes and scorpions, and over all the power of the enemy; and nothing will hurt you.
42勘 10:20 Nevertheless, do not rejoice at this, that the spirits submit to you, but rejoice that your names are written in heaven."
42勘 10:21 At that same hour Jesus rejoiced in the Holy Spirit and said, "I thank you, Father, Lord of heaven and earth, because you have hidden these things from the wise and the intelligent and have revealed them to infants; yes, Father, for such was your gracious will.
42勘 10:22 All things have been handed over to me by my Father; and no one knows who the Son is except the Father, or who the Father is except the Son and anyone to whom the Son chooses to reveal him."
42勘 10:23 Then turning to the disciples, Jesus said to them privately, "Blessed are the eyes that see what you see!
42勘 10:24 For I tell you that many prophets and kings desired to see what you see, but did not see it, and to hear what you hear, but did not hear it."
42勘 10:25 Just then a lawyer stood up to test Jesus. "Teacher," he said, "what must I do to inherit eternal life?"
42勘 10:26 He said to him, "What is written in the law? What do you read there?"
42勘 10:27 He answered, "You shall love the Lord your God with all your heart, and with all your soul, and with all your strength, and with all your mind; and your neighbor as yourself."
42勘 10:28 And he said to him, "You have given the right answer; do this, and you will live."
42勘 10:29 But wanting to justify himself, he asked Jesus, "And who is my neighbor?"
42勘 10:30 Jesus replied, "A man was going down from Jerusalem to Jericho, and fell into the hands of robbers, who stripped him, beat him, and went away, leaving him half dead.
42勘 10:31 Now by chance a priest was going down that road; and when he saw him, he passed by on the other side.
42勘 10:32 So likewise a Levite, when he came to the place and saw him, passed by on the other side.
42勘 10:33 But a Samaritan while traveling came near him; and when he saw him, he was moved with pity.
42勘 10:34 He went to him and bandaged his wounds, having poured oil and wine on them. Then he put him on his own animal, brought him to an inn, and took care of him.
42勘 10:35 The next day he took out two denarii, gave them to the innkeeper, and said, 'Take care of him; and when I come back, I will repay you whatever more you spend.'
42勘 10:36 Which of these three, do you think, was a neighbor to the man who fell into the hands of the robbers?"
42勘 10:37 He said, "The one who showed him mercy." Jesus said to him, "Go and do likewise."
42勘 10:38 Now as they went on their way, he entered a certain village, where a woman named Martha welcomed him into her home.
42勘 10:39 She had a sister named Mary, who sat at the Lord's feet and listened to what he was saying.
42勘 10:40 But Martha was distracted by her many tasks; so she came to him and asked, "Lord, do you not care that my sister has left me to do all the work by myself? Tell her then to help me."
42勘 10:41 But the Lord answered her, "Martha, Martha, you are worried and distracted by many things;
42勘 10:42 there is need of only one thing. Mary has chosen the better part, which will not be taken away from her."
42勘 11:1 He was praying in a certain place, and after he had finished, one of his disciples said to him, "Lord, teach us to pray, as John taught his disciples."
42勘 11:2 He said to them, "When you pray, say: Father, hallowed be your name. Your kingdom come.
42勘 11:3 Give us each day our daily bread.
42勘 11:4 And forgive us our sins, for we ourselves forgive everyone indebted to us. And do not bring us to the time of trial."
42勘 11:5 And he said to them, "Suppose one of you has a friend, and you go to him at midnight and say to him, 'Friend, lend me three loaves of bread;
42勘 11:6 for a friend of mine has arrived, and I have nothing to set before him.'
42勘 11:7 And he answers from within, 'Do not bother me; the door has already been locked, and my children are with me in bed; I cannot get up and give you anything.'
42勘 11:8 I tell you, even though he will not get up and give him anything because he is his friend, at least because of his persistence he will get up and give him whatever he needs.
42勘 11:9 "So I say to you, Ask, and it will be given you; search, and you will find; knock, and the door will be opened for you.
42勘 11:10 For everyone who asks receives, and everyone who searches finds, and for everyone who knocks, the door will be opened.
42勘 11:11 Is there anyone among you who, if your child asks for a fish, will give a snake instead of a fish?
42勘 11:12 Or if the child asks for an egg, will give a scorpion?
42勘 11:13 If you then, who are evil, know how to give good gifts to your children, how much more will the heavenly Father give the Holy Spirit to those who ask him!"
42勘 11:14 Now he was casting out a demon that was mute; when the demon had gone out, the one who had been mute spoke, and the crowds were amazed.
42勘 11:15 But some of them said, "He casts out demons by Beelzebul, the ruler of the demons."
42勘 11:16 Others, to test him, kept demanding from him a sign from heaven.
42勘 11:17 But he knew what they were thinking and said to them, "Every kingdom divided against itself becomes a desert, and house falls on house.
42勘 11:18 If Satan also is divided against himself, how will his kingdom stand? --for you say that I cast out the demons by Beelzebul.
42勘 11:19 Now if I cast out the demons by Beelzebul, by whom do your exorcists cast them out? Therefore they will be your judges.
42勘 11:20 But if it is by the finger of God that I cast out the demons, then the kingdom of God has come to you.
42勘 11:21 When a strong man, fully armed, guards his castle, his property is safe.
42勘 11:22 But when one stronger than he attacks him and overpowers him, he takes away his armor in which he trusted and divides his plunder.
42勘 11:23 Whoever is not with me is against me, and whoever does not gather with me scatters.
42勘 11:24 "When the unclean spirit has gone out of a person, it wanders through waterless regions looking for a resting place, but not finding any, it says, 'I will return to my house from which I came.'
42勘 11:25 When it comes, it finds it swept and put in order.
42勘 11:26 Then it goes and brings seven other spirits more evil than itself, and they enter and live there; and the last state of that person is worse than the first."
42勘 11:27 While he was saying this, a woman in the crowd raised her voice and said to him, "Blessed is the womb that bore you and the breasts that nursed you!"
42勘 11:28 But he said, "Blessed rather are those who hear the word of God and obey it!"
42勘 11:29 When the crowds were increasing, he began to say, "This generation is an evil generation; it asks for a sign, but no sign will be given to it except the sign of Jonah.
42勘 11:30 For just as Jonah became a sign to the people of Nineveh, so the Son of Man will be to this generation.
42勘 11:31 The queen of the South will rise at the judgment with the people of this generation and condemn them, because she came from the ends of the earth to listen to the wisdom of Solomon, and see, something greater than Solomon is here!
42勘 11:32 The people of Nineveh will rise up at the judgment with this generation and condemn it, because they repented at the proclamation of Jonah, and see, something greater than Jonah is here!
42勘 11:33 "No one after lighting a lamp puts it in a cellar, but on the lampstand so that those who enter may see the light.
42勘 11:34 Your eye is the lamp of your body. If your eye is healthy, your whole body is full of light; but if it is not healthy, your body is full of darkness.
42勘 11:35 Therefore consider whether the light in you is not darkness.
42勘 11:36 If then your whole body is full of light, with no part of it in darkness, it will be as full of light as when a lamp gives you light with its rays."
42勘 11:37 While he was speaking, a Pharisee invited him to dine with him; so he went in and took his place at the table.
42勘 11:38 The Pharisee was amazed to see that he did not first wash before dinner.
42勘 11:39 Then the Lord said to him, "Now you Pharisees clean the outside of the cup and of the dish, but inside you are full of greed and wickedness.
42勘 11:40 You fools! Did not the one who made the outside make the inside also?
42勘 11:41 So give for alms those things that are within; and see, everything will be clean for you.
42勘 11:42 "But woe to you Pharisees! For you tithe mint and rue and herbs of all kinds, and neglect justice and the love of God; it is these you ought to have practiced, without neglecting the others.
42勘 11:43 Woe to you Pharisees! For you love to have the seat of honor in the synagogues and to be greeted with respect in the marketplaces.
42勘 11:44 Woe to you! For you are like unmarked graves, and people walk over them without realizing it."
42勘 11:45 One of the lawyers answered him, "Teacher, when you say these things, you insult us too."
42勘 11:46 And he said, "Woe also to you lawyers! For you load people with burdens hard to bear, and you yourselves do not lift a finger to ease them.
42勘 11:47 Woe to you! For you build the tombs of the prophets whom your ancestors killed.
42勘 11:48 So you are witnesses and approve of the deeds of your ancestors; for they killed them, and you build their tombs.
42勘 11:49 Therefore also the Wisdom of God said, 'I will send them prophets and apostles, some of whom they will kill and persecute,'
42勘 11:50 so that this generation may be charged with the blood of all the prophets shed since the foundation of the world,
42勘 11:51 from the blood of Abel to the blood of Zechariah, who perished between the altar and the sanctuary. Yes, I tell you, it will be charged against this generation.
42勘 11:52 Woe to you lawyers! For you have taken away the key of knowledge; you did not enter yourselves, and you hindered those who were entering."
42勘 11:53 When he went outside, the scribes and the Pharisees began to be very hostile toward him and to cross-examine him about many things,
42勘 11:54 lying in wait for him, to catch him in something he might say.
42勘 12:1 Meanwhile, when the crowd gathered by the thousands, so that they trampled on one another, he began to speak first to his disciples, "Beware of the yeast of the Pharisees, that is, their hypocrisy.
42勘 12:2 Nothing is covered up that will not be uncovered, and nothing secret that will not become known.
42勘 12:3 Therefore whatever you have said in the dark will be heard in the light, and what you have whispered behind closed doors will be proclaimed from the housetops.
42勘 12:4 "I tell you, my friends, do not fear those who kill the body, and after that can do nothing more.
42勘 12:5 But I will warn you whom to fear: fear him who, after he has killed, has authority to cast into hell. Yes, I tell you, fear him!
42勘 12:6 Are not five sparrows sold for two pennies? Yet not one of them is forgotten in God's sight.
42勘 12:7 But even the hairs of your head are all counted. Do not be afraid; you are of more value than many sparrows.
42勘 12:8 "And I tell you, everyone who acknowledges me before others, the Son of Man also will acknowledge before the angels of God;
42勘 12:9 but whoever denies me before others will be denied before the angels of God.
42勘 12:10 And everyone who speaks a word against the Son of Man will be forgiven; but whoever blasphemes against the Holy Spirit will not be forgiven.
42勘 12:11 When they bring you before the synagogues, the rulers, and the authorities, do not worry about how you are to defend yourselves or what you are to say;
42勘 12:12 for the Holy Spirit will teach you at that very hour what you ought to say."
42勘 12:13 Someone in the crowd said to him, "Teacher, tell my brother to divide the family inheritance with me."
42勘 12:14 But he said to him, "Friend, who set me to be a judge or arbitrator over you?"
42勘 12:15 And he said to them, "Take care! Be on your guard against all kinds of greed; for one's life does not consist in the abundance of possessions."
42勘 12:16 Then he told them a parable: "The land of a rich man produced abundantly.
42勘 12:17 And he thought to himself, 'What should I do, for I have no place to store my crops?'
42勘 12:18 Then he said, 'I will do this: I will pull down my barns and build larger ones, and there I will store all my grain and my goods.
42勘 12:19 And I will say to my soul, 'Soul, you have ample goods laid up for many years; relax, eat, drink, be merry.'
42勘 12:20 But God said to him, 'You fool! This very night your life is being demanded of you. And the things you have prepared, whose will they be?'
42勘 12:21 So it is with those who store up treasures for themselves but are not rich toward God."
42勘 12:22 He said to his disciples, "Therefore I tell you, do not worry about your life, what you will eat, or about your body, what you will wear.
42勘 12:23 For life is more than food, and the body more than clothing.
42勘 12:24 Consider the ravens: they neither sow nor reap, they have neither storehouse nor barn, and yet God feeds them. Of how much more value are you than the birds!
42勘 12:25 And can any of you by worrying add a single hour to your span of life?
42勘 12:26 If then you are not able to do so small a thing as that, why do you worry about the rest?
42勘 12:27 Consider the lilies, how they grow: they neither toil nor spin; yet I tell you, even Solomon in all his glory was not clothed like one of these.
42勘 12:28 But if God so clothes the grass of the field, which is alive today and tomorrow is thrown into the oven, how much more will he clothe you--you of little faith!
42勘 12:29 And do not keep striving for what you are to eat and what you are to drink, and do not keep worrying.
42勘 12:30 For it is the nations of the world that strive after all these things, and your Father knows that you need them.
42勘 12:31 Instead, strive for his kingdom, and these things will be given to you as well.
42勘 12:32 "Do not be afraid, little flock, for it is your Father's good pleasure to give you the kingdom.
42勘 12:33 Sell your possessions, and give alms. Make purses for yourselves that do not wear out, an unfailing treasure in heaven, where no thief comes near and no moth destroys.
42勘 12:34 For where your treasure is, there your heart will be also.
42勘 12:35 "Be dressed for action and have your lamps lit;
42勘 12:36 be like those who are waiting for their master to return from the wedding banquet, so that they may open the door for him as soon as he comes and knocks.
42勘 12:37 Blessed are those slaves whom the master finds alert when he comes; truly I tell you, he will fasten his belt and have them sit down to eat, and he will come and serve them.
42勘 12:38 If he comes during the middle of the night, or near dawn, and finds them so, blessed are those slaves.
42勘 12:39 "But know this: if the owner of the house had known at what hour the thief was coming, he would not have let his house be broken into.
42勘 12:40 You also must be ready, for the Son of Man is coming at an unexpected hour."
42勘 12:41 Peter said, "Lord, are you telling this parable for us or for everyone?"
42勘 12:42 And the Lord said, "Who then is the faithful and prudent manager whom his master will put in charge of his slaves, to give them their allowance of food at the proper time?
42勘 12:43 Blessed is that slave whom his master will find at work when he arrives.
42勘 12:44 Truly I tell you, he will put that one in charge of all his possessions.
42勘 12:45 But if that slave says to himself, 'My master is delayed in coming,' and if he begins to beat the other slaves, men and women, and to eat and drink and get drunk,
42勘 12:46 the master of that slave will come on a day when he does not expect him and at an hour that he does not know, and will cut him in pieces, and put him with the unfaithful.
42勘 12:47 That slave who knew what his master wanted, but did not prepare himself or do what was wanted, will receive a severe beating.
42勘 12:48 But the one who did not know and did what deserved a beating will receive a light beating. From everyone to whom much has been given, much will be required; and from the one to whom much has been entrusted, even more will be demanded.
42勘 12:49 "I came to bring fire to the earth, and how I wish it were already kindled!
42勘 12:50 I have a baptism with which to be baptized, and what stress I am under until it is completed!
42勘 12:51 Do you think that I have come to bring peace to the earth? No, I tell you, but rather division!
42勘 12:52 From now on five in one household will be divided, three against two and two against three;
42勘 12:53 they will be divided: father against son and son against father, mother against daughter and daughter against mother, mother-in-law against her daughter-in-law and daughter-in-law against mother-in-law."
42勘 12:54 He also said to the crowds, "When you see a cloud rising in the west, you immediately say, 'It is going to rain'; and so it happens.
42勘 12:55 And when you see the south wind blowing, you say, 'There will be scorching heat'; and it happens.
42勘 12:56 You hypocrites! You know how to interpret the appearance of earth and sky, but why do you not know how to interpret the present time?
42勘 12:57 "And why do you not judge for yourselves what is right?
42勘 12:58 Thus, when you go with your accuser before a magistrate, on the way make an effort to settle the case, or you may be dragged before the judge, and the judge hand you over to the officer, and the officer throw you in prison.
42勘 12:59 I tell you, you will never get out until you have paid the very last penny."
42勘 13:1 At that very time there were some present who told him about the Galileans whose blood Pilate had mingled with their sacrifices.
42勘 13:2 He asked them, "Do you think that because these Galileans suffered in this way they were worse sinners than all other Galileans?
42勘 13:3 No, I tell you; but unless you repent, you will all perish as they did.
42勘 13:4 Or those eighteen who were killed when the tower of Siloam fell on them--do you think that they were worse offenders than all the others living in Jerusalem?
42勘 13:5 No, I tell you; but unless you repent, you will all perish just as they did."
42勘 13:6 Then he told this parable: "A man had a fig tree planted in his vineyard; and he came looking for fruit on it and found none.
42勘 13:7 So he said to the gardener, 'See here! For three years I have come looking for fruit on this fig tree, and still I find none. Cut it down! Why should it be wasting the soil?'
42勘 13:8 He replied, 'Sir, let it alone for one more year, until I dig around it and put manure on it.
42勘 13:9 If it bears fruit next year, well and good; but if not, you can cut it down.'"
42勘 13:10 Now he was teaching in one of the synagogues on the sabbath.
42勘 13:11 And just then there appeared a woman with a spirit that had crippled her for eighteen years. She was bent over and was quite unable to stand up straight.
42勘 13:12 When Jesus saw her, he called her over and said, "Woman, you are set free from your ailment."
42勘 13:13 When he laid his hands on her, immediately she stood up straight and began praising God.
42勘 13:14 But the leader of the synagogue, indignant because Jesus had cured on the sabbath, kept saying to the crowd, "There are six days on which work ought to be done; come on those days and be cured, and not on the sabbath day."
42勘 13:15 But the Lord answered him and said, "You hypocrites! Does not each of you on the sabbath untie his ox or his donkey from the manger, and lead it away to give it water?
